	<td valign="Top">
<center><b><font size="4">OPERATIONAL REPORT FROM THE</font></b></center>
<p>
<center><b><font size="4">EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE</font></b></center>
<p>
Recognizing that healthy companies and healthy profits are only
achieved by a relentless focus on pleasing the customer, we are
working hard to bring about fundamental change in the way Kmart
does business. Our mission is for Kmart to become the discount
store of choice for our desired customer-women between 25 and
45 years old, with children at home and with household incomes
between $20,000 and $50,000 per year.
<p>
To fulfill this mission, we are in the process of implementing
numerous merchandising and operational initiatives aimed at achieving
improved assortments, better in-stock positions, cleaner and more
orderly stores, and dramatic gains in customer service. All of
our actions are focused on a rapid return to profitability.
<p>
<b><font size="4">Specifically, our initiatives include:</font></b>
<ul>
<li><p>Improving our in-stock position is essential to the shopping
experience. Although we already have seen substantial improvement
in this area, we can still do much better. As recently as late
1994, Kmart stores were in-stock less than 90 percent of the
time. Following a series of initiatives last year, our in-stock
position at year-end 1995 was running at 96 percent. Our target
for 1996 is to achieve parity with our competitors by reaching
an in-stock position of 98 percent. </p></li>
<li><p>In 1995, we developed a high frequency prototype that provides
an improved store layout. The prototype features better lighting
and fixturing, improved signage, and a focused selection of consumables
such as paper products, soaps, snacks, and sodas, as well as frequently
purchased apparel and other merchandise, like socks and underwear.
Focusing on high-frequency items will drive repeat traffic into
our stores, improve our sales productivity, and build shopper
loyalty. We will roll this concept out to approximately 150 stores
in 1996. </p></li>
<li><p>Broadening our national brand offerings so that customers
see a powerful presentation of goods with improved depth and selection.
At the same time, building a select group of Kmart private label
brands that will complement and support our national brand strategy.
These Kmart-developed brands will include our Jaclyn Smith, Kathy
Ireland, Martha Stewart, American Fare and K-Gro labels, along
with several others. </p></li>
<li><p>Refining our promotional strategy to ensure that we offer
competitive prices across a clearly defined &quot;image list.&quot;
We will use the weekly advertising circular to offer customers
great deals at market-leading prices. </p></li>
<li><p>Customer service also is receiving considerable attention.
In 1995 we instituted a blind survey of our stores through a &quot;Mystery
Shopper&quot; program that gives store managers direct feedback
on customer perceptions. In 1995, our customer satisfaction rating
increased from 81 percent to 85.4 percent, which remains well
below an acceptable level of performance. In 1996, 50 percent
of the field management bonus will be tied to this measure. </p></li>
<li><p>Store appearance is a long-standing problem that we attacked
squarely in 1995 with a one-time shot of capital aimed at making
our stores sparkle. On an ongoing basis, our field management
will provide intense scrutiny of store appearance and customer
service across the Company. As part of this process, we have reduced
the number of stores that each district manager supports from
28 to 12. Likewise, we have reorganized the internal structure
of our stores to put in place a category management system that
gives our associates more direct responsibility for store performance
and customer service. </p></li>
</ul>
<p>
We firmly believe that all of these actions, taken together, will
have a dramatic impact on how our customers perceive Kmart, how
frequently they shop in our stores, and how much they buy each
visit. Increasing our customers' frequency and the amount they
purchase each visit, in turn, will have a dramatic impact on the
company's efforts to increase its profitability and enhance shareholder
value.
<p>
<font size="4" color="#0000FF">- KMART EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE<br>
- March 19, 1996<br>
</font>
<br>
<br>
